        🖨️ 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝘁 - 𝙸𝚗𝚍𝚒𝚎 𝚂𝚝𝚎𝚗𝚌𝚒𝚕
          prompt = A fully illustrated image produced in the specific aesthetic of Risograph printing — the stencil-based duplicator process that has become the defining medium of independent zine and art book publishing since its revival in the 2010s, its characteristic visual qualities the direct result of physical constraints that digital tools can simulate but never entirely replicate. The ink is the foundation of everything: Risograph uses soy-based inks in a limited range of named spot colors — the specific fluorescent pink whose saturation sits at the precise threshold between warm and electric, the flat navy whose depth reads as near-black in shadow areas but reveals its blue character in lighter values, the bright yellow of the process color that functions simultaneously as sunlight and as a graphic element, the forest green whose slightly warm bias distinguishes it immediately from the cooler cyan of conventional four-color printing — and each color is printed as a completely separate pass through the machine, the inks translucent rather than opaque. That translucency is the defining visual property: where two color layers overlap, they do not mix the way opaque inks do but instead produce additive blends whose specific hue is determined by the optical combination of two semi-transparent color layers over the paper surface below, the overlap zones reading as distinct third colors — pink over yellow producing a specific warm coral, navy over pink producing a rich purple whose specific hue exists nowhere in the individual ink colors, yellow over blue producing the specific slightly acid green of Riso overlap that has become a signature of the medium. The halftone dot screen is always visible. Risograph does not produce smooth gradients — tonal variation is achieved through a dot screen of the specific Riso resolution, the dots large enough to read individually at normal viewing distance, arranged in the regular grid pattern of screen printing rather than the stochastic distribution of photographic halftone, their presence transforming what would be a smooth gradient in another medium into a field of visible dots whose density varies with the tone it represents. This dot structure is especially visible in skin tones, sky gradients, and any area of the image where the illustration calls for subtle tonal variation — the dots making the mechanics of color reproduction visible as a design element rather than concealing them as a technical necessity. The paper shows through. Risograph is printed on uncoated stock, and the ink sits on the surface rather than sinking into a coated layer — the paper's own color and texture are integral to the image, the white of the stock functioning as the lightest tone in every color channel since the translucent inks cannot produce their own white, the surface tooth of uncoated paper giving the ink a very slight roughness at its edges rather than the hard, clean boundary of offset printing on coated stock. Registration between color passes is imprecise by nature. Each color layer is fed through the machine separately, and the mechanical tolerance of that process produces the characteristic slight misalignment of Riso color registration: the two or three color layers sitting a few pixels off from perfect alignment, creating the specific color fringing at the edges of forms where one layer slightly overhangs or underlaps the adjacent layer, the fringing not a defect but a signature — the visual proof that this image was produced by stacking physical layers of ink rather than rendered in software. The illustration style that has evolved around the Riso medium reflects its constraints: flat areas of unmodulated color rather than the painterly gradients and complex rendering that offset printing can handle, compositions organized into clearly separated color zones that exploit the translucency overlap rather than fighting against it, line work in the darkest available color that reads as near-black and provides the structural skeleton around which the translucent color layers are organized. The overall image belongs to the specific visual culture of the contemporary independent publishing scene — the zines, art books, limited-edition prints, and music packaging that have adopted Risograph as the medium of choice for work that values visible process, physical materiality, and the specific beauty of technical constraint over the seamless perfection of digital production.
